# Death of a Teenage Girl: Rise of AI Writing

Many people have an alter ego from their teenage years, a secret passion that kept them up till two in the morning on a school night. I bet you two iced Americanos that if you saw my picture from early high school, you wouldn't recognize me. You see, I went through the death of a teenage girl.

One of my best-kept secrets, which I will expose for this essay to give my words some credibility, is that I used to be a Wattpad author. If you never had the pleasure (or misfortune) of stepping into that corner of the internet, just know that there were multiple cases of twelve-year-old authors creating fanfictions there that were twice the length of the original book.

One argument that I often hear in defense of AI art is the reduction of barriers to entry — except that Wattpad didn’t have any. Anyone could publish and read, for free, anonymously, and from the comfort of their own bed.

And just in case you never experienced “artists’ high,” let me paint you a picture — I am sitting in bus number 151 on my way to school. It is 6:37, December, pitch-black outside because we are in Poland. The song *"Winter in the Dark"* by Lorde is playing on my tangled, wired headphones (I know, very on theme), and I am typing my soul away on my tiny iPhone 6, which shuts down every three stops because of the freezing temperatures.

I never wrote a better piece of literature than that morning, and never experienced the same profound sense of purpose as when I delivered a new chapter to my 20 readers.

Now I fear that this pure, human experience will be lost. That teenagers will never get to care about their art so deeply — to type with freezing fingers, to draw on the side of their notebook, to sing in the shower, to collect ring-pulls to make jewelry, to take their older brother’s guitar to a school trip, and to write secret poetry for their crush.

## Creativity vs. Consumption

There is a video essay by Josh Czuba, titled *“How I Trained My Mind to Create Instead of Consume.”* While listening, I came to a horrifying realization: I need to retrain myself to participate in creative writing again.

I need to put effort into setting my other work aside, put my phone on mute, and stare at a blank document waiting for the spark to come back.

I used to write before sleep, instead of sleep, between classes, during classes, after school, and even in the shower, which drove my parents crazy trying to figure out why the water bill was so high.

And then, university happened.

The discovery was so terrifying that I went to a therapist just to inform her, full of regret:

> “I am not a writer anymore.”

She advised me to schedule writing time once per day, and I really wanted to scream. Because the idea of “scheduling a writing session” seems the same as scheduling a quarter-hour break to cry in the bathroom during your first day at work. Just not human.

Obviously, I am aware that most professional authors write on the clock, but I was not a professional writer — I was a teenage girl yearning for the moon and stars. All I wanted was to feel even an ounce of the same passion and love for my craft as I did five years ago.

## And Then AI Arrived

And then…

*Did you know you can generate an entire plot with one prompt?*

*Make your characters come to life with our new AI image creator!*

*Can AI script a new generation of Hollywood movies?*

*Re-writing Shakespeare in Gen Z style with ChatGPT!*

Oh God. How did we get here?

I think back to the teenage girls on Wattpad — wordsmiths, creators, worldbuilders. Birthing literature, often in a foreign language, before even finishing high school. Making playlists to accompany new chapters, creating new countries full of dragons, celebrities, heated conflicts, and usually Draco Malfoy.

What happened to them?

Are they defending their paper in front of an academic committee for too many m-dashes?

Do they work in communications, writing captions for brainrot marketing videos?

Were they laid off from their dream position in journalism?

Do they still write?

## Questions for the Reader

I could talk about the legacy, the history of English and German literature trends, preservation of identity, and the political importance of books.

Instead, I will ask you some questions.

Would you prefer to have your wedding vows written in Gemini 3 Pro Thinking or Claude 4.6?

Or even better, which model would you employ to write your biography and feed it all your trauma?

How can you prompt Banana Pro to generate an illustrated book for your infant so it’s overstimulated from day one?

Why don’t you tell the college committee why you are so passionate about “civic collective action through local activation initiatives,” because that is what the Chat said to make a garage sale sound more impressive?

If you got all tensed up and said, *“Oh, I would never use AI for such things, that is crazy!”* — good.

Remember that uncomfortable feeling as the border between created and generated words grows fainter.

If your reaction was anything different, please seek help.

## Distracted

In his video, Josh said one sentence that struck me:

> “I wasted years of creativity on being distracted.”

Not busy. Not occupied. Not overloaded.

Distracted.

After reflecting further on how I allocate my time, I realized I can justify staying up to 3 a.m. to fix code for my pre-class work. But I can’t justify wasting time writing poetry on the balcony instead of sleeping.

I'm willing to go out of my way to submit another internship application, but I can’t commit to turning in this essay to the Column on time, because work takes priority.

I even caught myself thinking that arts and humanities students don’t really contribute much to the economy.

I immediately cursed myself, because since when do I think about maximizing stakeholder value?

How is it even possible that I became so distracted with things that five years ago couldn’t even occupy one chair in my heart, and somehow took over the whole stadium?

To finish this essay, I am staying up on a class night, writing in my gym clothes because I didn’t have time to change. My headphones are about to die, it’s one in the morning, and I finally feel free again.

And you could say:

> “Hey, it’s okay — you just grew up. Hobbies lose priority. Technology advances. Keep up or stay behind. That is just life.”

Maybe I grew up.

Or maybe I died, went through the classic death of a teenage girl.

My only request — don’t put an AI-generated epitaph on my grave.
